Test Plan: Load & Performance Testing for Optimized File Permission Agent
1. Objective
The primary objective of this test plan is to validate the performance, scalability, and functional correctness of the newly optimized File Permission Update Code under high-load conditions similar to the production incident where server outage occurred.

This plan focuses on:

Reproducing real-world traffic patterns observed during the incident timeframe.

Generating controlled heavy server load using automated load testing.

Evaluating whether the optimized agent performs reliably under stress.

Ensuring no functional regressions after optimization.

2. Background & Context
During a recent production incident, a server outage was observed under high traffic conditions. One of the contributing factors identified was a server-intensive agent responsible for updating file permissions to public when a meeting becomes active. Under peak load, this agent frequently failed, impacting system stability.

To address this, an optimized version of the agent has been developed. This test plan outlines the approach to validate its behavior under both functional and high-load scenarios.

3. Scope
In Scope
API endpoints that were actively invoked during the incident timeframe.

Load test automation suite creation for selected APIs.

Stressing the server by injecting high traffic using load tests.

Functional validation of the optimized agent.

Load and performance testing of the optimized agent.

Monitoring agent execution success, failures, and latency.

4. Test Strategy
4.1 Load Test Automation Suite
Identify API endpoints that were heavily used during the incident window.

Use OpenSearch/log analysis data to determine realistic request volume and concurrency.

Automate these APIs into a load testing suite (e.g., JMeter / k6 / Gatling).

Simulate peak and beyond-peak traffic to intentionally induce heavy server load.

4.2 Load Injection Strategy
Gradually ramp up load to baseline peak traffic.

Increase load beyond peak levels to stress the server.

Sustain load for a defined duration to observe agent stability.

This induced load will recreate conditions similar to the outage scenario.

5. Test Types
5.1 Functional Testing (Optimized Agent)
Purpose: Ensure the optimized agent works as expected under normal conditions.

Test Scenarios:

Agent triggers when a meeting is marked active.

File permissions are updated to public correctly.

Agent completes successfully without errors.

Correct handling of edge cases (re-trigger, partial updates, retries).

Acceptance Criteria:

100% success rate for valid inputs.

No data inconsistency or permission mismatch.

5.2 Load Testing (Optimized Agent)
Purpose: Validate agent performance under realistic high traffic.

Test Scenarios:

Concurrent meeting activations triggering the agent.

Agent execution under sustained API traffic.

Increased concurrency and throughput.

Metrics to Capture:

Agent execution time.

Success vs failure count.

CPU, memory, and thread utilization.

API response times and error rates.

Acceptance Criteria:

Agent completes within acceptable time limits.

Failure rate remains below defined threshold.

5.3 Stress Testing
Purpose: Identify breaking points and system limits.

Test Scenarios:

Load beyond peak production traffic.

Sudden traffic spikes.

Acceptance Criteria:

System degrades gracefully.

No cascading failures or server crashes.

Agent failures (if any) are controlled and logged.

